01":"1460–1501","1460–1501":"1460–1501","1462–1510":"1462–1510","1500–1540":"1500–1540","1400–1461":"1400–1461","1402–1460":"1402–1460","       1501":"1501","1402":"1402","1501":"1501","1500":"1500","1400":"1400","1510":"1510","1540":"1540","1462":"1462","after 1460":"after 1460","1461":"1461","1460":"1460","about 1498":"about 1498","Wiltenge, Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","England":"England, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Dunstable, Bedfordshire, England":"Dunstable, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Annabel","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Nottinghamshire and Derbyshire): variant of   Amable  , a derivative of the Old French and Middle English female personal name <i>Amabil</i>, <i>Amabel</i>, from Latin <i>amabilis</i> ‘lovable’. In some cases it may also be also a habitational name from Amble, Northumberland, recorded as <i>Amble</i> from 1203 onward but also as <i>Anebelle</i> (1292) and <i>Anebill</i> (1347)."],"variants":[{"name":"Anable","meanings":["English: variant of   Annable  ."]},{"name":"Hannibal","meanings":["German: from a post-humanist personal name, <i>Hannibal</i> (see 2 below).","English: post-medieval variant of   Annable  , from Middle English <i>Amabil</i>, <i>Annabel</i>. This female personal name fell out of fashion in the late Middle Ages, and the source of the surname was no longer recognized. It was re-interpreted in the 16th century by classically educated gentlemen as being the name of the Carthaginian general, Hannibal (247–182  BC ). The surname was also sometimes later re-etymologized as <i>honey</i> + <i>ball</i> or <i>bell</i>, hence spellings such as <b>Honeyball</b> and <b>Hunnibell</b>. In this new guise, it coincided with an established variant of <i>Annable</i> with initial <i>H-</i>.","History: There is no evidence for the use of <i>Hannibal</i> as a personal name in England before 1619, when Hannibal Gammon was rector of Mawgan in Pyder, Cornwall. As a medieval surname, it was borne by Matthew Hanibal (1255) and Peter Haniballus, both described as ‘civis Romanus’, and obviously Italians, but it is unlikely that either of these Italian merchants or moneylenders founded an English family."]},{"name":"Amable","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Old French and Middle English female personal name <i>Amabil</i>, <i>Amabel</i>, Latin <i>Amabilis</i> ‘lovable’. The Normans frequently made use of the Old French short form <i>Mabile</i> or <i>Mabel</i> (see   Mable  ) and, by dissimilation of <i>m</i> to <i>n</i>, developed a new form, <i>Anabel</i>, which gave rise to surnames such as   Annable   and   Hannibal  ."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Annabel was born in 1460, in England, United Kingdom, his father, William Annabel, was 60 and his mother, Maria Rockley, was 58. He married Elizabeth Stanley about 1498, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1501, in Essex, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1460–       1501":"1460–1501","1460–1501":"1460–1501","1462–1510":"1462–1510","1500–1540":"1500–1540","1400–1461":"1400–1461","1402–1460":"1402–1460","       1501":"1501","1402":"1402","1501":"1501","1500":"1500","1400":"1400","1510":"1510","1540":"1540","1462":"1462","after 1460":"pärast 1460","1461":"1461","1460":"1460","about 1498":"umbes 1498","Wiltenge, Essex, England":"Essex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Suffolk, England":"Suffolk, England","Dunstable, Bedfordshire, England":"Dunstable, Bedfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1460–       1501":"1460–1501","1460–1501":"1460–1501","1462–1510":"1462–1510","1500–1540":"1500–1540","1400–1461":"1400–1461","1402–1460":"1402–1460","       15